




TY  - JOUR
T1  - Nobel Lecture: The Economic Way of Looking at Behavior
AU  - Becker, Gary S.
Y1  - 1993/06/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261880
DO  - 10.1086/261880
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 385
EP  - 409
VL  - 101
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - An important step in extending the traditional theory of individual rational choice to analyze social issues beyond those usually considered by economists is to incorporate into the theory a much richer class of attitudes, preferences, and calculations. While this approach to behavior builds on an expanded theory of individual choice, it is not mainly concerned with individuals. It uses theory at the micro level as a powerful tool to derive implications at the group or macro level. The lecture describes the approach and illustrates it with examples drawn from my past and current work.
AB  - An important step in extending the traditional theory of individual rational choice to analyze social issues beyond those usually considered by economists is to incorporate into the theory a much richer class of attitudes, preferences, and calculations. While this approach to behavior builds on an expanded theory of individual choice, it is not mainly concerned with individuals. It uses theory at the micro level as a powerful tool to derive implications at the group or macro level. The lecture describes the approach and illustrates it with examples drawn from my past and current work.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261880
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261880
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Wage Inequality and the Rise in Returns to Skill
AU  - Juhn, Chinhui
AU  - Murphy, Kevin M.
AU  - Pierce, Brooks
Y1  - 1993/06/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261881
DO  - 10.1086/261881
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 410
EP  - 442
VL  - 101
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Using data from the March Current Population Survey, we document an increase over the past 30 years in wage inequality for males. Between 1963 and 1989, real average weekly wages for the least skilled workers (as measured by the tenth percentile of the wage distribution) declined by about 5 percent, whereas wages for the most skilled workers (as measured by the ninetieth percentile of the wage distribution) rose by about 40 percent. We find that the trend toward increased wage inequality is apparent within narrowly defined education and labor market experience groups. Our interpretation is that much of the increase in wage inequality for males over the last 20 years is due to increased returns to the components of skill other than years of schooling and years of labor market experience. Our primary explanation for the general rise in returns to skill is that the demand for skill rose in the United States over this period.
AB  - Using data from the March Current Population Survey, we document an increase over the past 30 years in wage inequality for males. Between 1963 and 1989, real average weekly wages for the least skilled workers (as measured by the tenth percentile of the wage distribution) declined by about 5 percent, whereas wages for the most skilled workers (as measured by the ninetieth percentile of the wage distribution) rose by about 40 percent. We find that the trend toward increased wage inequality is apparent within narrowly defined education and labor market experience groups. Our interpretation is that much of the increase in wage inequality for males over the last 20 years is due to increased returns to the components of skill other than years of schooling and years of labor market experience. Our primary explanation for the general rise in returns to skill is that the demand for skill rose in the United States over this period.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261881
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261881
Y2  - 2024/03/22
